<h1>HomeTest Operational Swimlanes</h1>
<div class="sub">How the national HomeTest service runs at steady state. Seven operational processes, seven actors. The patient is one of them: Abdul, Mark, Layla, and everyone like them. The other six are the people who get the right test to the right person, return the right result, and trigger the right next step.</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="main">
<div class="intro">
<h2>How to read this</h2>
<p>Seven operational lanes, each describing a distinct process at steady state. Eight actors thread through them — Commissioner, Joe (supplier), Patient, Clinician (the configuration-specific clinician who initiates and reads the result), David (NHS Commercial), Aisha (Clinical / CSG), Ngozi (IG / DPO) and Priya (NHSE Platform). Where a cell is empty, that actor genuinely has no role at that stage.</p>
<p>This is the <strong>steady-state national operating model</strong>, not the route to get there. Discovery / Alpha / Beta selection processes (including specific EOIs for Acute Use Case Partner and COPD test cases) sit outside scope. The live service support model carries two tiers: a Day-1 tier covering beta cutover and early-life support, and the steady-state tier shown on this page from go-live (April onward). Day-1 mechanics are interim. Where steady-state behaviour is different, the steady-state behaviour is what the lanes describe.</p>
<p>Cells flagged <span class="gap-flag" style="margin-top:0;">like this</span> need a decision or evidence before they can be confirmed. Cells flagged <span class="new-flag" style="margin-top:0;">like this</span> reflect recent content updates.</p>
<div style="margin-top:14px;padding-top:12px;border-top:1px solid rgba(0,0,0,0.08);font-size:12px;padding-top:14px;"><a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Status.html" style="color:#005EB8;font-weight:700;text-decoration:none;letter-spacing:0.3px;">See all open items across the model →</a></div>
</div>
<div style="background:#FFF8E6;border:1px solid #F0DCA0;border-radius:8px;padding:11px 16px;margin:0 0 18px;font-size:12px;color:#4C6272;line-height:1.55;">
<strong style="color:#9A6700;">Five foundation-level capabilities sit alongside these lanes:</strong> Post-market surveillance (regulatory: MHRA, adverse events, periodic safety updates), Pathway integration (alignment with national transformation programmes per therapeutic area), Independent assurance (third-party assurance distinct from internal Clinical Safety), Contract Management (post-execution lifecycle for each call-off), and Ongoing Evidence Generation (continuous evidence accrual into the Assurance Model). All cross-cutting foundation capabilities. See <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Teamwork.html#cap-12" style="color:#9A6700;font-weight:700;text-decoration:none;">Teamwork (Cap-12 to Cap-16)</a>.
 </div>
<div style="margin: 18px 0 22px; background: linear-gradient(135deg, #F4F8FC 0%, #E8F1F6 100%); border: 1px solid #B5D4E5; border-left: 5px solid var(--nhs-blue); border-radius: 14px; padding: 22px 26px;">
  <div style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 800; letter-spacing: 1.6px; color: var(--nhs-blue); text-transform: uppercase; margin-bottom: 10px;">How to read this page</div>
  <ol style="margin: 0; padding-left: 22px; font-size: 13px; color: var(--text-sec); line-height: 1.7;">
    <li><strong>Lanes</strong> are work streams. Each lane is one actor&apos;s view of the work from find through to operate.</li>
    <li><strong>Cells</strong> describe what that actor does at each stage. Foundation cells are universal; overlay cells vary by configuration.</li>
    <li><strong>The configuration toggle</strong> above (HIV, PSA-AS, iron deficiency anaemia, Community-init) highlights cells relevant to one configuration. Off-config cells dim.</li>
    <li><strong>The actor key</strong> (the row of persona cards below) switches which lane is in view. Click any card to jump to that actor&apos;s lane.</li>
    <li><strong>The synthesis paragraph</strong> at the foot of each lane summarises what is happening across the actors at that point in the work.</li>
  </ol>
