<div style="padding:0 16px 16px;">
<div class="routes-box">
<h4>Three routes</h4>
<p class="route"><strong>Route A: Standard.</strong> Full bar across all five dimensions. End-to-end capability against an API. Scaled tier on every dimension. Default route for suppliers offering end-to-end test delivery.</p>
<p class="route"><strong>Route B: Light-touch.</strong> Constrained scope (single test, single LA pilot, PoC). Core tier across all dimensions; scaled tier on dimensions material to scope. Stops smaller suppliers being priced out by balance-sheet alone.</p>
<p class="route"><strong>Route C: Partnership.</strong> NHS provider partners and acute use case partners. Design-and-validation partnership rather than commercial supplier contract. IP vests in NHSE. Distinct criteria reflecting the partnership archetype.</p>
<p class="route"><strong>Growth pathway.</strong> Route B can progress to Route A by demonstrating scaled-tier evidence through live operation over a defined period. Annual default review or triggered by material change.</p>
</div>
<div class="note-box">
<strong>Why this design.</strong> <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Supplier Onboarding Framework.html" style="color:#005EB8;font-weight:700;text-decoration:underline;">Onboard once per API</a>, lighter-weight per test. Publish the criteria; don't gate them. Self-assessment first, human review second. Tiered thresholds so the floor doesn't exclude. No defensive filtering. Every artefact exists once. Supplier experience is a design input. Anchored in the working position that a good supplier onboarding model is mostly self-service: the centre has to make it really easy for suppliers to bring themselves in, not act as a bottleneck.
 </div>
<div class="decision-box">
<h4>Open decisions</h4>
<p><strong>Royal Mail Health terms.</strong> Volume discounts apply per shipper rather than aggregated across NHS suppliers. The only way to leverage those terms would be for NHS to centralise kit fulfilment and stock management. Not viable without fundamental model change.</p>
<p><strong>Panel-of-tests sequencing.</strong> How panels of tests are introduced to commissioners over time, and the order in which they enter the catalogue, not yet defined.</p>
</div>
<div class="note-box" style="background:#f1f5f9;border-color:#cbd5e1;color:#334155;margin-top:14px;">
<strong>Supplier offboarding.</strong> Onboarding is one half of the supplier lifecycle. Voluntary exit and performance-driven removal are covered in <strong>Lane 6 (Marketplace stewardship)</strong> alongside resilience and market evolution. Detailed offboarding mechanics (notice periods, evidence thresholds, appeals, commissioner transition support) are still to be designed.
 </div>
</div>
