<div class="note-box">
<strong>NHS Online payment flow as reference architecture.</strong> A useful precedent. The plumbing involves several NHS payment systems: <em>PbR</em> (Payment by Results — the activity-based payment regime), <em>CDS</em> (Commissioning Data Set — where activity is recorded), <em>SUS</em> (Secondary Uses Service — the national activity data warehouse), <em>HRG</em> (Healthcare Resource Group — the classification used to value activity), <em>NHSBSA</em> (NHS Business Services Authority — pharmacy payments), and <em>OPCS</em> (the procedure code classification used in CDS). For NHS Online the flows are: ICB host pays NHS Online via NHS Standard Contract; ICB local pays Diagnostic Provider via PbR using CDS / SUS / HRG data; NHSBSA pays Pharmacy via the Drug Tariff. The friction point: a central platform generates local activity that local commissioners did not plan or contract for. HomeTest faces the same gap at scale.
 </div>
<div class="note-box" style="background:#fef3c7;border-color:#f5d787;color:#92580a;">
<strong>The tariff position.</strong> No live NHS tariff code yet covers home testing, but a Patient-Not-Present tariff design is now in flight. NHSE Strategic Finance has drafted a <strong><span class="cfg-mark" data-config="psa-as">PSA Active Surveillance</span> Monitoring Episode</strong> tariff with a glide-path: shadow 26/27, dual-run at 50% in 27/28, live at 100% in 28/29. Five reconciliation mechanisms sit underneath it (bundled episode, efficiency-factor offset, glide-path, capacity-release credits, ICB-level capitated AS top-up). The longer-term "no tariff code" framing is therefore wrong in flavour for <span class="cfg-mark" data-config="psa-as">PSA</span>; for <span class="cfg-mark" data-config="hiv">HIV</span> the LA budget route remains the position. Planned volumes and opt-in commissioning still apply where the tariff has not yet landed.
 </div>
<div class="decision-box">
<h4>Open decisions</h4>
<p><strong>Capacity ceilings and overflow.</strong> Local commissioning budgets cap volumes. No overflow mechanism if demand spikes. Working position is that paying for excess is cheaper than engineering caps. Central backstop not yet agreed.</p>
<p><strong>Three-tier pricing structure (mobilisation + activity + volume floor).</strong> Activity tier measured on cost per valid result, not flat per-kit. Per-kit was rejected through the RFI and supplier forums. Subscription was rejected at strategic level. The three-tier shape gives suppliers a predictable floor while incentivising return rates on the activity tier. Final activity-unit position is A9 in the recommendation paper. Health economics modelling substantiates the activity-tier cost base.</p>
<p><strong>Addressable market sizing.</strong> No quantified model exists. Working order-of-magnitude is one million tests and roughly £50m at scale. Without a hard number the options paper stays narrative.</p>
<p><strong>Centralised payment.</strong> Working position is that payment flows run between commissioner and supplier directly. A centralised invoicing model has been flagged as a longer-term option but not designed.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>


