<h4 style="color:var(--ig-dark);">How this lane works in steady state</h4>
<p><strong>The legal-direction document set.</strong> When a configuration sits outside the lawful basis the platform already carries, the route is a legal direction. The set is four artefacts: approved DPIA, technical specification, privacy notice, and Secretary of State letter. The DPIA is the core. The technical specification and privacy notice face the public and explain what is being done with the data. The Secretary of State letter is the formal sign-off, drafted in PTT, signed at the top of NHSE, and published online with the rest of the set.</p>
<p><strong>The test for whether a legal direction is required.</strong> Five factors: what data, for what purpose, who is the controller, whether data is matched against other datasets (secondary uses), whether data is anonymous or pseudonymised. Run early in SHAPE, not at the end of CONTRACT. The widest plausible list of data controllers and data flows is asked for upfront, not bolted on later, because revising a direction mid-flight is painful.</p>
<p><strong>Assumption discipline.</strong> When IG counterparts are slow to respond, the framework documents the working assumption, takes SLT sign-off, and embeds it in the programme board pack. The platform keeps moving while the formal IG channel is pressed. Assumptions are explicit, evidenced and traceable, so the gap between assumption and final decision is small when the answer lands.</p>
<p><strong>Data controllers are a growing list, not a fixed set.</strong> Under Pathway 1 (LA-commissioned, <span class="cfg-mark" data-config="hiv">Self-init</span>) the controllers are NHSE for the foundation, the LA commissioner for the testing purpose, and the supplier as processor. Under Pathway 2 (acute-initiated) acute trusts join as controllers for their testing purpose. Under Pathway 3 (<span class="cfg-mark" data-config="ida">GP-initiated</span>) GP practices join as controllers. The framework asks for the widest plausible list of controllers upfront when a new clinical area enters scope (the Wayfinder precedent), rather than returning for incremental directions each time a configuration adds a new controller type.</p>
<p><strong>Legal-direction sequencing has a six-month lead time.</strong> A new or amended legal direction takes around six months end to end. The MI scope and data flows that the direction will cover have to be locked before the direction is requested. If the scope shifts after the direction is in flight, the request restarts, and the next available answer is two cycles away. The discipline is to converge the MI scope deliberately and only then trigger the direction. Re-asking PTT mid-flight burns goodwill as well as time.</p>
<p><strong>Little and often. Shared outcomes.</strong> IG and delivery engage continuously rather than at gate moments, working to one shared view of what success looks like. The pattern is a steady cadence of short, focused IG conversations through the lifecycle, not a single heavyweight DPIA review at the end. It removes the cost of revisions, the cost of late surprises, and the cost of conflicting informal advice teams seek when the formal route is too slow. Standard inputs (data flow diagram, controllers map, lawful basis statement) have agreed quality expectations so the same evidence is not reproduced three different ways across three different reviews.</p>
</div>
<div class="decision-box">
<h4>Open decisions</h4>
<p><strong>Data controller framework.</strong> Federated multi-controller model agreed in principle (NHSE for foundation, commissioner for testing purpose, supplier as processor). Joint-controller ruled out. Exact controller designation per configuration still being scoped. Lawful basis position (direct consent vs legal directions) unresolved at SLT level.</p>
<p><strong>IAO appointed.</strong> NHSE policy requires the IAO to be a permanent NHSE employee; the role is now filled (confirmed at the June 2026 Delivery Board). <strong>The earlier go-live blocker is closed;</strong> remaining IG sign-off tracks through the DPIA.</p>
<p><strong>PTT scope is per clinical area.</strong> PTT teams are organised by clinical area, not by platform. The team that decides directions for the current clinical area is not the same team that decides directions for primary care, secondary care diagnostics, or screening outside the current condition. As the platform scales, it engages multiple PTT teams in parallel. The framework needs to be portable across them, with a clear handover pattern when a new clinical area first comes into scope.</p>
<p><strong>National data infrastructure alignment.</strong> How HomeTest's IG framework dovetails with FDP (Federated Data Platform) and SPR (Single Patient Record) governance. Each carries its own lawful basis and controller designation; HomeTest aligns to them rather than creating parallel governance.</p>
</div>
