<!-- SYNTHESIS -->
<div class="synth">
<h2>What the swimlanes expose</h2>
<p><strong>The framework administrator role is the hardest new capability.</strong> Whether NHSE self-administers or outsources, somebody has to run continuous supplier admission, performance management, pricing compliance, market health monitoring. That's a standing team, not a project function.</p>
<p><strong>The centre's role is matchmaker, not contract counterparty.</strong> The centre runs onboarding, sets standards, builds integration, monitors market health. It does not sign local contracts on behalf of LAs, own billing, or operate logistics.</p>
<p><strong>Systematisation is the work.</strong> Most of these processes need to be designed and built as standing capabilities, not as project-mode workarounds. The framework administrator role and the centre's standing onboarding, performance, and market-health functions are where this concentrates.</p>
<p><strong>The financial lane is still the weakest part of the design.</strong> The <span class="cfg-mark" data-config="psa-as">PSA Active Surveillance</span> Monitoring Episode tariff is now in design with a 26/27 to 28/29 glide-path, but the addressable market model, central funding for the platform itself, and overflow backstop remain unresolved.</p>
</div>

